    "instruction": "Using the existing kernel variable 'metric_anomalies', aggregate anomalies by cmdb_id to create 'service_anomaly_summary' with these fields: cmdb_id; n_kpi_anomalies = number of distinct kpi_name with >=1 anomaly; total_anomaly_count = sum of anomaly_count across KPIs; earliest_anomaly_timestamp = min(earliest_anomaly_timestamp) across KPIs; max_severity_ratio = maximum of (max_value_in_window / p95) across KPIs with safe handling: if p95==0 and max_value_in_window>0 set ratio = inf, if both zero set ratio = 0. Return up to top 20 rows sorted first by n_kpi_anomalies descending, then by max_severity_ratio descending. Include columns: cmdb_id, n_kpi_anomalies, total_anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_severity_ratio. Also return the total count of distinct cmdb_id services that have at least one anomaly."
}

{
    "analysis": "You aggregated metric anomalies per service into 'service_anomaly_summary' and identified 68 services with anomalies. Many services show their earliest anomaly at 2024-01-24T19:24:00Z, and several services (e.g., ts-admin-travel-service, ts-food-service, ts-ui-dashboard, ts-user-service, ts-order-service, ts-train-service, ts-auth-service) are top candidates by number of KPI anomalies and/or severity. According to the workflow, with multiple service-level candidates we must use traces to determine which faulty service is the most downstream in call chains (i.e., likely root cause). If traces are insufficient, logs will be used next. Therefore the next step is to inspect trace telemetry during the incident window for the top candidate services to see which services have trace anomalies (high latency or abnormal trace metrics) and what trace features are available.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load 'trace.csv', parse timestamps in UTC, and filter rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 19:21:31 to 2024-01-24 19:51:31 UTC. From the kernel variable 'service_anomaly_summary' take the top 20 services sorted by n_kpi_anomalies desc then max_severity_ratio desc (extract their cmdb_id list). Filter trace rows to only those cmdb_id in that top-20 list. Aggregate these filtered trace rows by cmdb_id to compute: trace_count, distinct_trace_names (as a comma-separated string, limit to 10 names), earliest_trace_timestamp (min), mean_value, and p95_value of 'value'. Store the aggregated result as 'trace_summary'. Return up to 20 rows of 'trace_summary' sorted by trace_count desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_count, distinct_trace_names, earliest_trace_timestamp, mean_value, p95_value. Also return the total number of trace rows in the window for these top-20 services and the list of the selected top-20 cmdb_id values."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis for the top-20 anomalous services shows many services with heavy trace activity and high tail latencies around 2024-01-24T19:24:00Z. Notably, among the candidate services allowed by the task (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service), several (ts-train-service, ts-travel-service, ts-order-service, ts-auth-service) already appeared in the trace summary with large p95 latencies, and their earliest traces align with the metric anomalies at ~19:24 UTC. According to the diagnosis workflow and the rule that the root-cause must be chosen from the provided possible root cause components, we should now inspect metric anomalies specifically for those five services to identify which resource KPIs are faulty (e.g., socket, mem, diskio, cpu) and their severity and timing. This will let us determine which of the five is the most likely root cause and which failure reason (e.g., socket error, high memory, high disk I/O, network latency) is indicated by metrics.",
