    "instruction": "From the existing kernel variable 'metric_anomalies', filter rows to only the five candidate services: ['ts-auth-service','ts-order-service','ts-route-service','ts-train-service','ts-travel-service']. For these rows compute and return a compact table (limit 50 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95, severity_ratio (max_value_in_window / p95 with handling: if p95==0 and max_value>0 set severity_ratio = inf, if both zero set 0). Also include a small summary: for each of the five services, report the number of distinct KPI anomalies and the earliest anomaly timestamp across its KPIs. Return the filtered table and the per-service summary."
}

{
    "analysis": "You filtered metric anomalies to the five allowed candidate services (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service). Each service shows multiple KPI anomalies (7 distinct KPIs each, 35 rows total). Metric anomalies begin around 2024-01-24T19:24:00Z for most services. Trace analysis showed large tail latencies (high p95) for several of these services—particularly ts-train-service and ts-travel-service—indicating performance degradation in the call chain. Because multiple service-level candidates are faulty at the same level, we must now use logs to distinguish which service is the true root cause and to determine the failure reason (e.g., socket error, high memory, disk I/O). Error logs may contain explicit socket/network errors or application exceptions that point to the root cause resource. Therefore the next step is to examine normalized log features and raw error log messages for these five services within the incident window.",
